This is one of the three historic <b>Walking Dredges</b> &quot;that were primary working machines that made the Tamiami highway construction project possible. The dredge's patented engineering played a pivotal role in the speed, safety, and financing in the struggle to build the Tamiami Trail through the Florida Everglades.&quot; [<a href="http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/feature/places/13000318.htm" rel="nofollow">1</a>]

<i>Florida Memory</i> has other photos of the Walking Dredge in their <a href="http://floridamemory.com/solr-search/results/?q=(Walking Dredge OR tt:Walking Dredge^10)&amp;query=Walking Dredge" rel="nofollow">collection</a> -- including this additional <a href="http://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/25989" rel="nofollow">photo</a> of the Walking Dredge at work on the construction of the Tamiami Trail.

One of the three dredges, &quot;The Bay City Walking Dredge #489&quot; has been preserved by the National Park Service's National Register of Historic Places, as a National Historic Mechanical Engineering Landmark, and can be visited in a somewhat <a href="http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/feature/places/13000318.htm" rel="nofollow">remarkable display</a> at Collier-Seminole State Park in Naples, Florida.

Photos of the dredge can also be seen on the National Register of Historic Place's <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nationalregister/tags/walkingdredges/">Flickr pages</a>, and you can read and see more about how this unique dredge works <a href="http://files.asme.org/asmeorg/Communities/History/Landmarks/1280.pdf" rel="nofollow">here</a>.

<i>Florida Memory</i> uploaded a photo that shows the end result (in 1927) of the construction through the Everglades!

